The opening of i3 has been a very mysterious opening in all times. That opening has been a weapon for many top players in the world.
Mr Yamaguchi considered i3 to be his favorite opening for long long time
I was a big fan of i3 about 10 years ago.
At that time I made a lot of research about it.
As teacher Renju_liu_t showed you in past 3 lessons,
as a part of the preparation for 1995,
but unfortunately I didn't get the opportunity to use it,
because that WC nobody opened i3 against me.
why you did not open it against somebody else?
5 years later, I published these variants
to open i3 in WC is a kind of suicide
The top players can control the game in i3 as black,
even if they dont know sure win.
i3 offers perfect ways for black to have total control until the end of game,
and, to get only a draw (if lucky) is not sufficient for me
Therefore I cannot afford to open i3 in WC finals.
It seems all is quite clear with 6-j7,
you have studied it for three lessons with Renju_liu_t
and it is time to focus on other 6th moves.
it became clear also about lessons before, because up to now nobody said this is such a big black advantage
This 6th move is symmetrical with j7,
but is black's tactics after this 6th exactly the same or not?
Having learned the variants in past 3 weeks,

i think not same. dege problems

While this way of winning is good after such 6th move,

and white has lots of ways to defend here.
What about this 6th move, have you seen it?
In the history, this 6th move (together with 6-j9) was more famous,
It was often played about 15 years ago.
This was the common start of black sure win attack.
However, many players became lazy, and played moves nearly without thinking,
so some tricky players changed 6th move to j7,
Many players were punished by easy trap
because they didnt care to watch for the difference.
